        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-08-02 10:37:05.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 10:\n\nBuild Unstable \n\nhttps://jenkins.onap.org/job/policy-drools-applications-maven-clm-master/57/ : UNSTABLE (skipped)\n\nNo problems were identified. If you know why this problem occurred, please add a suitable Cause for it. ( https://jenkins.onap.org/job/policy-drools-applications-maven-clm-master/57/ )\n\nLogs: https://logs.onap.org/production/vex-yul-ecomp-jenkins-1/policy-drools-applications-maven-clm-master/57",
        "patchset_number": 10
      },
      {
        "id": "0a06b72cce6dea67087507bc7877dc7c75937594",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 477,
          "name": "Jorge Hernandez",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jorge.hernandez-herrero@att.com",
          "username": "jhh"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-08-03 14:25:59.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 10:\n\nWe traditionally were using in drools-pdp and drools-applications for scripts, scripts with no extensions, so their invocation could be kept generic regardless the scripting language used underneath.   The other convention is to use \"-\" instead of \"_\".   I know that the previous .jmx script from amsterdam leaked with \".sh\", but better to stick to common conv.  Is there a reason to deviate from the original convention with this script?",
        "patchset_number": 10
      },
      {
        "id": "59bb6f788452659180a37c4269599790bc96789c",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 811,
          "name": "Jim Hahn",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jrh3@att.com",
          "username": "jrh3"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2018-08-03 14:45:19.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 10: -Code-Review\n\n> We traditionally were using in drools-pdp and drools-applications\n > for scripts, scripts with no extensions, so their invocation could\n > be kept generic regardless the scripting language used underneath. \n >  The other convention is to use \"-\" instead of \"_\".   I know that\n > the previous .jmx script from amsterdam leaked with \".sh\", but\n > better to stick to common conv.  Is there a reason to deviate from\n > the original convention with this script?\n\nIt follows the same conventions as testsuites/stability.  However, I can remove the \".sh\" extension, if desired.  Regarding \"-\" instead of \"_\", though, I find \"_\" much easier to use, as the clipboard \"selection\" operation in putty, double-click, does not span hyphens, while it does span underscores.  If the convention is to use \"-\", then that particular convention should be changed going forward - it's a major pain to not be able to use double-click.  (IMO, this is a handicap accessibility issue.)",
        "patchset_number": 10
      },
      {
        "id": "aa0c2830bfa76d69349d96cc7c09cdadc7a8ca30",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 477,
          "name": "Jorge Hernandez",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jorge.hernandez-herrero@att.com",
          "username": "jhh"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-08-03 15:19:35.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 10: Code-Review-1\n\nLet's stick with the original convention for these repos to try to keep a consistent apperance for files of the same type.  We can have a separate general conversation to change it for all files, but would be an all-or-nothing changing at the same time.  Key thing is consistency.  As a note, I don't experience the double-click selection behavior that you're mentioning.",
        "patchset_number": 10
      },
      {
        "id": "b1efbbe8023e21da148a27ae604a231ac0caeb24",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 811,
          "name": "Jim Hahn",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jrh3@att.com",
          "username": "jrh3"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2018-08-03 15:25:41.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 10:\n\n> Let's stick with the original convention for these repos to try to\n > keep a consistent apperance for files of the same type.  We can\n > have a separate general conversation to change it for all files,\n > but would be an all-or-nothing changing at the same time.  Key\n > thing is consistency.  As a note, I don't experience the\n > double-click selection behavior that you're mentioning.\n\nMy mistake, it was in eclipse, not putty.  I'll modify the scripts as specified.  Note: testsuites/stability still follows a different convention.",
        "patchset_number": 10
      },
      {
